{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631294"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:25:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:25:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17363"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17363"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10053"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115149"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10053"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97157"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5487"},{"type":"tags","id":"7819"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23542"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23546"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115149"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is conducting a meta-analysis of clinical trials examining the effectiveness of a new antihypertensive medication. The studies were conducted across different countries with varying patient populations and healthcare settings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the main advantage of using a random-effects model in this meta-analysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provides narrower confidence intervals","Accounts for between-study and within-study variation","Gives more weight to smaller studies","Assumes all studies share the same true effect","Eliminates heterogeneity between studies"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe main advantage of a random-effects model is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccounts for between-study and within-study variation\u003C/strong\u003E. This is particularly important when studies are conducted across different populations and settings, as it acknowledges that true treatment effects may vary between studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvides narrower confidence intervals\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as random-effects models typically produce wider, more conservative confidence intervals. \u003Cstrong\u003EGives more weight to smaller studies\u003C/strong\u003E is not the main advantage, although smaller studies may receive relatively more weight compared to fixed-effect models. \u003Cstrong\u003EAssumes all studies share the same true effect\u003C/strong\u003E is actually the assumption of fixed-effect models, not random-effects models. \u003Cstrong\u003EEliminates heterogeneity between studies\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because random-effects models account for heterogeneity rather than eliminating it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERandom-effects models are particularly appropriate when there is significant heterogeneity between studies, as they provide a more realistic and conservative estimate of the overall treatment effect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Random-effects models account for both within-study and between-study variation in meta-analyses.","Random-effects models are appropriate when there is significant heterogeneity between studies in a meta-analysis.","Random-effects models provide more conservative estimates with wider confidence intervals than fixed-effect models."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 43; pg. 457."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97157"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17363"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97157"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T13:56:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T13:56:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10053"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115149"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatis